# Container Launch Fixes

This plan outlines the fixes for container shortcut creation, game auto-launching, and x86_64 container boot failures.

## Proposed Changes

### Game Settings Shortcut Creation Fix
The current logic creates a completely new container every time the user clicks "Game Settings" for a game, instead of creating a Shortcut (`.desktop` file) that reuses an existing container.

#### [MODIFY] [ContainerDetailFragment.java](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/ContainerDetailFragment.java)
- Update the `createShortcutForAppId > 0` block inside the Save button listener.
- Stop creating a raw container using `manager.createContainerAsync()` without generating a shortcut.
- Instead, query existing containers for one matching the selected `wineVersion`.
  - **If found**: Use it as the target container.
  - **If not found**: Create a new container to act as the target.
- Generate a `[Desktop Entry]` `.desktop` file representing the Game Shortcut inside the target container's desktop directory.
- Initialize a [Shortcut](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/container/Shortcut.java#21-317) object, pass all overriden UI properties to it using [putExtra()](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/container/Container.java#324-334), and call [saveData()](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/container/Container.java#407-445) so they persist in the `[Extra Data]` block.

### Game Auto-Launch Fix
When launching a game directly from the Library without a configured Shortcut, [UnifiedActivity.kt](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/UnifiedActivity.kt) sets a temporary `container.executablePath` which is completely ignored by [XServerDisplayActivity](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/XServerDisplayActivity.java#137-2018). This results in Wine File Manager (`wfm.exe`) opening instead of the game.

#### [MODIFY] [UnifiedActivity.kt](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/UnifiedActivity.kt)
- In [launchSteamGame()](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/UnifiedActivity.kt#950-1009), when no [Shortcut](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/container/Shortcut.java#21-317) exists for the game (`shortcut == null`):
  - Automatically create a `.desktop` shortcut inside the selected default container's desktop directory.
  - Set the [Exec](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/container/Container.java#107-110) parameter of this new shortcut to correctly point to the game's executable (e.g., `wine "A:\path\to\game.exe"`).
  - Pass the newly created `shortcut.file.path` to [XServerDisplayActivity](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/XServerDisplayActivity.java#137-2018) via Intent, instead of just the `container_id`.

### x86_64 Container Boot Failure Fix
The `x86_64` containers are failing to boot on newer architectures (like the Adreno 840/SD 8 Elite which lacks 32-bit execution) due to `wowbox64` environment misconfiguration, causing wine crashes immediately at launch.

#### [MODIFY] [GuestProgramLauncherComponent.java](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/xenvironment/components/GuestProgramLauncherComponent.java)
- Update the `wowbox64` DLL handling to ensure `libwow64fex.dll` / `wowbox64.dll` are loaded correctly for `x86_64`, protecting against Wine process exceptions during WoW64 thunks transition.

## Verification Plan

### Manual Verification
1. **Test Game Settings**: Go to the Library, click "Game Settings" on a game, configure settings (e.g., select Proton 9.0), and click the checkmark. Verify it saves successfully and *does not* create an empty "Container-N" without a shortcut.
2. **Test Game Auto-Launch**: Go to the Library and click "Play" on a game that has no Game Settings configured. Verify that the game's executable automatically launches when the container starts.
3. **Test x86_64 Boot**: Go to Containers, create a new `x86_64` container, and click "Run" on it. Verify that the XServer display activity starts and Wine boots to the desktop/wrapper without crashing.
